00:14:58.060 --> 00:14:59.360
&gt;&gt; Raza Panjawani: Thank you.

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:03.060
When the WIPO Copyright
Treaty was adopted

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:05.260
and the United States was
considering enacting the Digital

00:15:05.260 --> 00:15:07.990
Millennium Copyright Act,
the consideration I believe

00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:10.940
at the time -- I wasn't
there personally --

00:15:10.940 --> 00:15:13.760
was that there was a necessity
to provide protections

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:16.380
for rights holders in
order to encourage them

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:21.290
to provide digital goods and
to distribute them online.

00:15:21.290 --> 00:15:26.580
One of the things we have seen
is that DRM is not necessary

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:27.880
for a number of business models.

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:30.340
And business owners are entitled to
choose how they wish to distribute,

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:34.840
but we've seen the adoption of
iTunes taking a DRM-free stance,

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:40.000
we have seen CD Projekts GOG.com
game distribution platform sells

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.860
both classic and newer
releases without DRM,

00:15:43.860 --> 00:15:47.670
the Tor Book in print also
releases ebooks without DRM.

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:51.260 position:56%
In the last 7 to 10 years, we've
seen a move away from the assumption

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:55.100
that DRM is absolutely necessary
to have a digital economy.

00:15:55.100 --> 00:15:58.440
Considering that Section
1201 takes that assumption

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:02.190 position:56%
and then burdens the public's rights
to engage in non- infringing uses

00:16:02.190 --> 00:16:04.190
in order to provide
these protections,

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:07.310
I think it's worth reengaging
in a cost-benefit analysis

00:16:07.310 --> 00:16:12.390
of to what extent do we still need
these very high barriers in order

00:16:12.390 --> 00:16:15.200
to encourage digital distribution.

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:17.850
Beyond that, I think it's
worth talking about the fact

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:24.200 position:56%
that how effective 1201 has actually
been in curtailing digital piracy,

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:26.680
which is something that
Congress explicitly called

00:16:26.680 --> 00:16:32.260
out in its legislative history as
a reason for enacting Section 1201.

00:16:32.260 --> 00:16:34.320
In our comments, we pointed
to a number of statements

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:37.790
by various copyright industries
decrying the level of piracy

00:16:37.790 --> 00:16:40.200
that is occurring online
and digitally.

00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:43.880 position:56%
And I -- while I know some folks
have responded by saying that, well,

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:46.880
we need to look at the
digital markets we've created,

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:52.910
the content that has been allegedly
made available by circumventing DRM

00:16:52.910 --> 00:16:55.480
and that is available in these
marketplaces is the same,

00:16:55.480 --> 00:16:56.900
it's not separate.

00:16:56.900 --> 00:17:02.700
And I think separating these two
sort of conflates correlation

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:06.550
and causation, that because of
DRM, we now have digital markets.

00:17:06.550 --> 00:17:08.880
I don't think that's
necessarily true.

