look at the NII Whitepaper

00:20:36.440 --> 00:20:38.920
that made the recommendations that
led to the adoption of the DMCA,

00:20:38.920 --> 00:20:42.290
it was very explicit in saying
that in this new environment,

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:45.130
the copyright owners would look to
technology to protect their rights

00:20:45.130 --> 00:20:47.610
and that would be a very
valuable tool in terms of helping

00:20:47.610 --> 00:20:49.730
to promote the growth
of digital commerce

00:20:49.730 --> 00:20:53.180
but that technology alone would
be insufficient to meet that goal,

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:56.730
and that legal protections
alone would also be insufficient

00:20:56.730 --> 00:20:58.030
to meet that goal.

00:20:58.030 --> 00:21:01.850
And it was the combination of the
two that were going to be required

00:21:01.850 --> 00:21:04.340
to meet the objective of
encouraging people to sort of jump

00:21:04.340 --> 00:21:08.400
with both feet into a new digital
environment in which content,

00:21:08.400 --> 00:21:10.640
in a very high quality,
was put at risk.

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:14.080
And I think the experience has
been that that's what has resulted

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:17.160
from the DMCA, that people have
relied on the legal protections,

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:18.780
combined with the technological
protections,

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:22.640
to get into these businesses with
both feet, perhaps more quickly

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:24.290
than otherwise would
have been the case.

00:21:24.290 --> 00:21:26.670
I -- I know that the
availability of the --

00:21:26.670 --> 00:21:28.530
the WIPO Treaties and
their discussions,

00:21:28.530 --> 00:21:31.370
the DMCA were directly
relevant to the adoption

00:21:31.370 --> 00:21:33.140
of CSS as a protection for DVD.

00:21:33.140 --> 00:21:35.690
It was what led to the
introduction of the DVD,

00:21:35.690 --> 00:21:38.160
which became the fastest
growing consumer platform --

00:21:38.160 --> 00:21:41.120
consumer electronics platform
up to that time in history.

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:45.910
Jonathan is right that that --
that that technology was hacked

00:21:45.910 --> 00:21:48.370
and that there were tools
available to defeat it,

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:51.800
but that's also what
spawned much of the --

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:54.740
the precedent that we have
right now in the DMCA is

00:21:54.740 --> 00:21:57.930
in enforcement litigation under
the DMCA dealing with those things.

00:21:57.930 --> 00:22:00.600
And it's not -- and the
objective was never to say

00:22:00.600 --> 00:22:03.220
that these technologies
would be hack-proof

00:22:03.220 --> 00:22:05.290
or that there would never
be anyone who would be able

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:08.620
to access the tools to do it,
or that would be able to figure

00:22:08.620 --> 00:22:10.740
out a way to do it, but that
you would keep these things

00:22:10.740 --> 00:22:12.040
out of the mainstream.

00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:14.880
And that's exactly what that
litigation had the effect of doing.

00:22:14.880 --> 00:22:17.750
And you know, Mr. Zuck talks
about going into the Best Buy

00:22:17.750 --> 00:22:19.050
