And I think it's important and
worth mentioning that the people

00:27:55.960 --> 00:27:59.320
that make use of DRM don't like it.

00:27:59.320 --> 00:28:02.920
It's -- it's not enjoyable to --
to go through the process of trying

00:28:02.920 --> 00:28:05.490
to use technical protection
measures on your products.

00:28:05.490 --> 00:28:08.420
It increases consumer support
costs and everything else.

00:28:08.420 --> 00:28:11.660
It's simply been a necessary
tool in preventing piracy.

00:28:11.660 --> 00:28:14.540
And I can say that it's certainly
been a very successful tool

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:17.470
in the context of software as well.

00:28:17.470 --> 00:28:20.730
And in the app market that
I represent, the distinction

00:28:20.730 --> 00:28:24.260
between software and content
is becoming continually blurred

00:28:24.260 --> 00:28:25.560
as well.

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:27.690
So TPMs are used, not only for
the software itself but also

00:28:27.690 --> 00:28:29.260
for the content that's
embedded in --

00:28:29.260 --> 00:28:31.930
in software where some
of the piracy occurs.

00:28:31.930 --> 00:28:35.750
If I've got an app that's teaching
you yoga positions or something

00:28:35.750 --> 00:28:37.970
like that, sometimes the piracy
involves pulling the content

00:28:37.970 --> 00:28:41.010
out of the app and
repurposing it in another app.

00:28:41.010 --> 00:28:44.850
So TPMs have proven useful
in the software market.

00:28:44.850 --> 00:28:46.620
And then, the final
point is this notion

00:28:46.620 --> 00:28:49.390
about it expanding beyond
its original intention.

00:28:49.390 --> 00:28:51.690
And I -- I feel like that
comes up over and over again.

00:28:51.690 --> 00:28:54.180 position:56%
And in this context, I always remind
everyone that I'm not a lawyer.

00:28:54.180 --> 00:28:57.450 position:56%
But it's my understanding that where
those things have been adjudicated,

00:28:57.450 --> 00:29:01.260
they've come out in favor of a
more restrictive interpretation

00:29:01.260 --> 00:29:03.260
of -- of the DMCA.

00:29:03.260 --> 00:29:06.660
So I mean, I -- the -- you know,
whether it's garage door openers

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:09.950
or printer cartridges
and things like that,

00:29:09.950 --> 00:29:13.590
I think there's some fairly strong
precedents in place to suggest

00:29:13.590 --> 00:29:17.650
that it should be focused on
-- on copyright infringement.

00:29:17.650 --> 00:29:20.280
And the -- and the jail-breaking
legislation is another example,

00:29:20.280 --> 00:29:23.660
I think, of where the
system worked to --

00:29:23.660 --> 00:29:25.860 position:56%
to, you know, modify the environment

00:29:25.860 --> 00:29:29.600
in which people are getting overly
experimental in the use of 1201.

00:29:29.600 --> 00:29:32.260
But none of that, I
think, undermines the value

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:34.700
that it's played in what has
been a very successful market,

00:29:34.700 --> 00:29:38.610
and I think we should be very
cautious about upending that.

00:29:38.610 --> 00:29:39.910
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:29:39.910 --> 00:29:41.210
Mr. Band?

00:29:41.210 --> 00:29:42.960
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: So going --
going back to your question about,

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:45.380
you know, the number of cases,
I think you're right, there --

00:29:45.380 --> 00:29:49.720
there have been relatively few
1201 cases, certainly relative

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:53.680
to the number of, let's
say, of 512 cases.

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:58.820 position:56%
And it's always important when we're
talking about 1201 to also keep

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:03.740
in mind that it's part of this
bigger construct of the DMCA.

00:30:03.740 --> 00:30:08.690
But one of the reasons why there's
been relatively few 1201 cases,

00:30:08.690 --> 00:30:12.590
it seems to me, is that it's
-- it's really broadly drafted.

00:30:12.590 --> 00:30:15.110
It talks about, not only
the act of circumvention,

00:30:15.110 --> 00:30:20.450
but it talks about trafficking,
then there's also 1201(b).

00:30:20.450 --> 00:30:26.370 position:56%
The early cases, you know, went very
strongly in favor of rights holders,

00:30:26.370 --> 00:30:34.790
and so, there was very -- there
just hasn't been a need for the --

00:30:34.790 --> 00:30:38.260
the litigation because it's
-- it's been -- it's --

00:30:38.260 --> 00:30:40.230
it's been so broadly interpreted.

00:30:40.230 --> 00:30:44.720
So -- so then, the action
really has shifted very much

00:30:44.720 --> 00:30:46.720
to the rulemaking because,
you know, there --

00:30:46.720 --> 00:30:50.350
you have all these people
who are adversely affected,

00:30:50.350 --> 00:30:52.330
and if you're adversely
affected by the DMCA,

00:30:52.330 --> 00:30:56.450
I mean you have two choices, you
could sort of go ahead and engage

00:30:56.450 --> 00:31:00.040
in the activity and hope that,
in the event of litigation,

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:06.380
that you'll end up with, you know,
you'll end up in the right court,

00:31:06.380 --> 00:31:09.860
right, that you'll end up in the
-- in the Federal Circuit, I guess,

00:31:09.860 --> 00:31:12.420
or the Sixth Circuit, as
opposed to the Ninth Circuit.

00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:15.540
But, you know, yeah, good luck
in making sure that that happens.

00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:18.040
If you're on the defendant side,
you don't really get to choose

00:31:18.040 --> 00:31:20.620
where the action is filed.

00:31:20.620 --> 00:31:23.570
And you know, that's one choice.

00:31:23.570 --> 00:31:26.570
Or the choice is to -- to
-- to go to the rulemaking.

00:31:26.570 --> 00:31:30.250
And so, so much of the
activity and the energy is

00:31:30.250 --> 00:31:34.220 position:56%
on the rulemaking side because, you
now, at least there is a rulemaking.

00:31:34.220 --> 00:31:35.960
So we're glad for that.

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:43.730
But that's why, you know,
because the DMCA is so broad

00:31:43.730 --> 00:31:46.960
and has been interpreted so
broadly by some circuits, you know,

00:31:46.960 --> 00:31:50.860
that's pushed all the activity and
the focus onto the rulemaking side

00:31:50.860 --> 00:31:57.130
and that's why so much -- so many
of us are so intent on trying

00:31:57.130 --> 00:32:01.350
to get the -- the rulemaking
to work better than it is.

00:32:01.350 --> 00:32:02.650
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:32:02.650 --> 00:32:03.950
Ms. Greene?

00:32:03.950 --> 00:32:05.250
&gt;&gt; Robyn Greene: Thank you.

00:32:05.250 --> 00:32:08.770
I was actually just going to
say some of what was just stated

00:32:08.770 --> 00:32:11.600
with regard to the reason why
there is not a tremendous amount

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:16.410
of litigation and the fact that
there have been favorable decisions

00:32:16.410 --> 00:32:18.940
in -- in previous court cases.

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:22.110
What I do want to note about that
though is that it is impossible

00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:25.510
to calculate the chilling effect
that those previous court cases,

00:32:25.510 --> 00:32:31.060
even though they were ruled on
favorably, has had on the market.

00:32:31.060 --> 00:32:34.570
Entrepreneurs who are just trying
to enter a marketplace may not want

00:32:34.570 --> 00:32:37.120
to take the risk that all
of the efforts that they go

00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:39.900
to to develop a new product,
to innovate, and to launch it

00:32:39.900 --> 00:32:43.470
in the marketplace may be for
naught as a result of litigation,

00:32:43.470 --> 00:32:46.690
even if they might
eventually win that litigation.

00:32:46.690 --> 00:32:49.650
And so, that -- that is
a -- a great concern.

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:53.480
And then, to the extent that it
has been, you know, pushed --

00:32:53.480 --> 00:32:58.070
the litigation has been pushed
to the rulemaking process.

00:32:58.070 --> 00:33:01.100
I do still think there is
a chill in the marketplace

00:33:01.100 --> 00:33:04.040
and a chill specifically
in activities

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:07.520
that are very clearly not
related to copyright infringement,

00:33:07.520 --> 00:33:11.540
such as security research, and the
burdens of that rulemaking process,

00:33:11.540 --> 00:33:13.580
which I know we'll
be discussing later,

00:33:13.580 --> 00:33:19.160
I think do oftentimes go outside of
the question of the effectiveness

00:33:19.160 --> 00:33:21.940
of TPMs in -- in helping
the marketplace,

00:33:21.940 --> 00:33:27.910
and in fact sometimes favor the
chill of that type of competition.

00:33:27.910 --> 00:33:29.740
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:33:29.740 --> 00:33:34.440 position:56%
So turning from the
effectiveness and the role of the --

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:37.780
the current law, I think we wanted
to explore a little bit some

00:33:37.780 --> 00:33:44.920 position:56%
of the proposed changes to 1201,
and really one of the central points

00:33:44.920 --> 00:33:47.640
of dispute, or disagreement
that we saw in the comments,

00:33:47.640 --> 00:33:53.650
is this idea that there is or
should be a nexus within 1201

00:33:53.650 --> 00:33:55.560
with copyright infringement.

00:33:55.560 --> 00:33:59.910
We had a, you know, large number of
comments supporting the -- the --

00:33:59.910 --> 00:34:01.300
the model obviously

00:34:01.300 --> 00:34:04.320
and the Unlocking Technology
Act that's been proposed

00:34:04.320 --> 00:34:09.780
that would limit circumvention
violations to those undertaken

00:34:09.780 --> 00:34:12.140
for the purpose of infringement.

00:34:12.140 --> 00:34:17.190
In response, we had several
comments saying that the --

00:34:17.190 --> 00:34:20.030
that accessing a copyrighted
work for purposes

00:34:20.030 --> 00:34:24.110
of consumption alone may not
implicate an exclusive right,

00:34:24.110 --> 00:34:29.260
and indeed, that type of activity
is -- is really the, you know,

00:34:29.260 --> 00:34:33.290
one of the -- the foundational
reasons why Section 1201

00:34:33.290 --> 00:34:34.590
was enacted.

00:34:34.590 --> 00:34:37.810
So I'd like to sort of explore
that debate a little bit.

00:34:37.810 --> 00:34:46.260
What are your views as to
proposals to incorporate a nexus

00:34:46.260 --> 00:34:49.790
to infringement within 1201?

00:34:49.790 --> 00:34:51.470
Mr. Adler?

00:34:51.470 --> 00:34:53.820
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: Oh, there
is a nexus to infringement

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:56.060
in 1201, but it's not in 1201 --

00:34:56.060 --> 00:34:57.360
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Oh,
microphone, please.

00:34:57.360 --> 00:34:59.850
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: There is
a nexus to infringement

00:34:59.850 --> 00:35:02.070
in 1201, but it's not in 1201(a).

00:35:02.070 --> 00:35:08.280
1201(a) is about access
controls, and "access" is not part

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:12.810
of the exclusive rights of
a copyright owner under 106.

00:35:12.810 --> 00:35:18.260
But obviously, access to the work
is the threshold issue with respect

00:35:18.260 --> 00:35:20.940
to whether or not uses of the work

00:35:20.940 --> 00:35:25.720
that implicate the exclusive
rights are going to occur.

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:30.730
If you look at -- at the way
Congress structured 1201,

00:35:30.730 --> 00:35:36.240
1201(a) was designed to deal with
the question of access independent

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:41.210
of the issue of infringement
because access to the work, again,

00:35:41.210 --> 00:35:46.320
was the question about whether or
not consumers were going to be able

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:50.160 position:56%
to exploit the marketplace and
whether there would be a marketplace

00:35:50.160 --> 00:35:53.000
of these works online to exploit.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:59.540 position:56%
When you look at -- at 1201(b),
1201(b) doesn't address the question

00:35:59.540 --> 00:36:04.850
of circumvention of a
technological protection measure

00:36:04.850 --> 00:36:10.120
that protects rights of a
copyright owner under section 106

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:13.840
and Title 17, specifically
because it recognizes

00:36:13.840 --> 00:36:18.590 position:56%
that those rights are themselves
subject to exceptions like fair use.

00:36:18.590 --> 00:36:21.860
But that's why those two questions
have to be looked at differently.

00:36:21.860 --> 00:36:25.280
The issue of access is
not about infringement.

00:36:25.280 --> 00:36:30.570
And to the extent that Congress
did seek to allow copyright owners

00:36:30.570 --> 00:36:34.660
to utilize technological protection
measures to deal with the issue

00:36:34.660 --> 00:36:39.540 position:56%
of infringement, that was done in
1201(b) where the balance was struck

00:36:39.540 --> 00:36:43.190
in recognizing limitations
and exceptions like fair use,

00:36:43.190 --> 00:36:47.230
while still suggesting that even
though there already are remedies

00:36:47.230 --> 00:36:49.400
in the law to deal
with infringement,

00:36:49.400 --> 00:36:53.090
technological measures can still
help a copyright owner be able

00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:55.440
to deal with that by
at least making sure

00:36:55.440 --> 00:36:59.250
that to the extent they do use
technological protection measures

00:36:59.250 --> 00:37:02.790
to protect exclusive rights,
that those are not subject

00:37:02.790 --> 00:37:06.160
to a marketplace that's rife
with availability of the means

00:37:06.160 --> 00:37:08.600
to circumvent those measures.

00:37:08.600 --> 00:37:09.900
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:37:09.900 --> 00:37:11.240
Mr. Band?

00:37:11.240 --> 00:37:16.090
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: So I -- I think
the premise of 1201(a) was --

00:37:16.090 --> 00:37:18.440
Allan's right, it's about access.

00:37:18.440 --> 00:37:21.900
But it's about access -- I
think what everyone had in mind

00:37:21.900 --> 00:37:23.620
and everyone thought they
were talking about was access

00:37:23.620 --> 00:37:25.600
to something you hadn't
paid for, right?

00:37:25.600 --> 00:37:30.860
I mean, it was -- the idea was,
you know, it was -- it was --

00:37:30.860 --> 00:37:34.070
it was like getting, you know, and
the people were talking about sort

00:37:34.070 --> 00:37:36.400
of getting access to cable
television that, you know, to --

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:39.230
get access -- getting access
to the premium channel

00:37:39.230 --> 00:37:40.530
that you hadn't paid for.

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:43.630
That's what it was -- but that's
what I think everyone really had

00:37:43.630 --> 00:37:44.930
in their mind.

00:37:44.930 --> 00:37:49.610
And certainly not the situation
that Mr. Lowe is dealing

00:37:49.610 --> 00:37:54.230
with in the automotive context
about a person not being able

00:37:54.230 --> 00:38:00.850
to access his own software in
his own car for the purpose

00:38:00.850 --> 00:38:07.490
of making sure that he doesn't pay
marked up prices for repair parts,

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:12.450
and that -- and that that was
not at all what was contemplated.

00:38:12.450 --> 00:38:16.650
Now, one can debate
what the words say

00:38:16.650 --> 00:38:19.690
and how they probably should be
-- properly should be interpreted,

00:38:19.690 --> 00:38:24.380
but I think it is fair to say
that there's no policy reason

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:27.660 position:56%
within the confines of the
Copyright Act or within the confines

00:38:27.660 --> 00:38:33.200
of Section -- of Title 17, for
there to be any restrictions

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:37.070
on a person's ability to
access their own property,

00:38:37.070 --> 00:38:38.370
their own copies.

00:38:38.370 --> 00:38:39.690
It's one thing to say
I shouldn't be able

00:38:39.690 --> 00:38:43.760
to access something I haven't
paid for, but if I've paid for it

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:46.560
and it's in my possession,
you know, why --

00:38:46.560 --> 00:38:48.410
why should there be
a legal framework

00:38:48.410 --> 00:38:51.250
that protects my ability
to access that?

00:38:51.250 --> 00:38:54.390
And so, that's why, you
know, we think the -- the --

00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:58.020
the Technology Unlocking Act makes
sense and that's why, you know --

00:38:58.020 --> 00:39:02.550
and -- and -- and whether it's --
it's through a statutory change

00:39:02.550 --> 00:39:07.660
or through a much more
liberal application of the --

00:39:07.660 --> 00:39:11.690
of the rulemaking in the
case of, at least software

00:39:11.690 --> 00:39:16.810
where we see this problem
most pervasively, you know,

00:39:16.810 --> 00:39:21.180
we would be able to sort of
simplify your work significantly

00:39:21.180 --> 00:39:27.950
and not have the DMCA basically
regulating the entire U.S. economy.

00:39:27.950 --> 00:39:30.300
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: So earlier we
heard about the various types

00:39:30.300 --> 00:39:35.450
of digital distribution, and is
your theory that 1201 should --

00:39:35.450 --> 00:39:37.400
should be limited to --
consumers should be able

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:38.740
to access what they have paid for?

00:39:38.740 --> 00:39:43.030 position:56%
