00:42:06.290 --> 00:42:09.850
The problem with requiring a
nexus to infringement for 1201(a),

00:42:09.850 --> 00:42:13.020
where you're dealing with the
issue of access, is that it fails

00:42:13.020 --> 00:42:17.630
to recognize that access to a work
has its own independent economic

00:42:17.630 --> 00:42:21.060
value, whether or not
someone is going to infringe

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:22.930
as a result of that access.

00:42:22.930 --> 00:42:24.920
For example, you know, we
hear all the time in --

00:42:24.920 --> 00:42:28.230
in the book industry that the
difference between the use

00:42:28.230 --> 00:42:32.820 position:56%
of printed books and -- and
digital -- books in digital formats,

00:42:32.820 --> 00:42:36.480
whether they're in ebooks that
you -- you have, you know,

00:42:36.480 --> 00:42:39.860
that you're looking at in a
device, or whether you're --

00:42:39.860 --> 00:42:42.620
you're actually reading
a book online,

00:42:42.620 --> 00:42:45.560
is the fact that reading
a book is not something

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:47.800
that actually exploits one

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:50.170
of the exclusive rights
of a copyright owner.

00:42:50.170 --> 00:42:51.470
That's true.

00:42:51.470 --> 00:42:54.380
But the purpose of putting
a book on the marketplace,

00:42:54.380 --> 00:42:57.890
the purpose of actually creating
a work of original expression

00:42:57.890 --> 00:43:00.720
in book form, is ultimately
to have people read it,

00:43:00.720 --> 00:43:03.120
and that's where the
economic value is.

00:43:03.120 --> 00:43:08.400
So the notion that the only way
rights holders can protect access

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:12.060
to their works, or control
access to their works online,

00:43:12.060 --> 00:43:14.710
is if they are able
to show that the means

00:43:14.710 --> 00:43:18.390
by which they do it is directly
related to addressing the issue

00:43:18.390 --> 00:43:21.750
of infringement, neglects the
whole notion of what the real value

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:24.870
of these works is in the
way they're used in ways

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:28.250
that don't involve
infringement at all.

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:29.660
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:43:29.660 --> 00:43:30.990
Did you want to respond
to that quickly or --

00:43:30.990 --> 00:43:32.290
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: Oh well, yeah.

00:43:32.290 --> 00:43:34.940
I don't -- I don't want to
monopolize, but I mean, I -- I --

00:43:34.940 --> 00:43:37.810
I -- you know, a lot of
it could be taken care

00:43:37.810 --> 00:43:39.130
of conceivably in the drafting.

00:43:39.130 --> 00:43:42.130
But even if we're not -- it --
it would seem to me that if I --

00:43:42.130 --> 00:43:47.240
if I, let's say, rent a -- a book,
right, and I -- I -- I'm allowed --

00:43:47.240 --> 00:43:52.420
entitled to it based on my
rental fee to have it for a week,

00:43:52.420 --> 00:43:57.670
and I fiddle with the software so
that I can keep it another week,

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:02.450
you know, that seems to me
that might get into this area

00:44:02.450 --> 00:44:06.630
of the kinds of, you know,
what we're -- what -- what --

00:44:06.630 --> 00:44:08.640
what we may be talking
about, that it --

00:44:08.640 --> 00:44:12.590
it conceivably could be
still subject to 1201(a),

00:44:12.590 --> 00:44:14.290
especially to the extent that my --

00:44:14.290 --> 00:44:16.000
you know, in order to
continue reading it,

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:21.570
I need to continue making copies
of it, RAM copies and so forth,

00:44:21.570 --> 00:44:28.810 position:56%
that are of more than a -- you know,
of more than a transitory period.

00:44:28.810 --> 00:44:32.530
So you know, I think even in that
case, it would conceivably --

00:44:32.530 --> 00:44:35.310
depending on how you draft it,
it would still be within the --

00:44:35.310 --> 00:44:38.930
you know, the scope of
what I'm thinking of.

00:44:38.930 --> 00:44:40.230
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:44:40.230 --> 00:44:41.530
Mr. Dow?

00:44:41.530 --> 00:44:42.830
&gt;&gt; Troy Dow: So -- so
Allan is absolutely right.

00:44:42.830 --> 00:44:44.800
The absence of a nexus
to infringement

00:44:44.800 --> 00:44:46.200
in the statute is quite deliberate.

00:44:46.200 --> 00:44:48.150
In fact, proposals
like the ones you find

00:44:48.150 --> 00:44:49.800
in the Unlocking Technology
Act are not new.

00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:52.940
Those were proposals that were made
at the time the DMCA was considered

00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:57.960 position:56%
and they were rejected for a variety
of reasons, including that really

00:44:57.960 --> 00:45:00.770
to have done that would have made
Section 1201 rather duplicative

00:45:00.770 --> 00:45:03.650
of Section 106, and that was not
the objective of the Statute.

00:45:03.650 --> 00:45:06.860
What Congress saw at the time
that they did this was a world

00:45:06.860 --> 00:45:09.970
in which you had the type of
scenario that Allan just described

00:45:09.970 --> 00:45:12.770
where the value to the -- where
the benefit to the consumer

00:45:12.770 --> 00:45:15.900 position:56%
and the value to the copyright owner
is derived from access to the work,

00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:18.650
not necessarily from the exercise
of the Section 106 rights.

00:45:18.650 --> 00:45:21.480
So the ability to access a work,
whether it be a book or a song

00:45:21.480 --> 00:45:24.530
or a movie or, you know, any
other form of expressive work,

00:45:24.530 --> 00:45:26.810
doesn't require you to copy
it, doesn't require you

00:45:26.810 --> 00:45:29.310
to distribute it, doesn't require
you to publicly perform it,

00:45:29.310 --> 00:45:33.120
but that the value is derived from
your ability to access at the time.

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:35.600
The thing that was talked about
was the celestial jukebox.

00:45:35.600 --> 00:45:38.450 position:56%
We've sort of gone to that model
across the board for different types

00:45:38.450 --> 00:45:40.890
of expressive works, and
Congress had that in mind.

00:45:40.890 --> 00:45:42.720
That's what -- what -- what
the intended result would be.

00:45:42.720 --> 00:45:45.260
And the fact that we are
quickly and continually moving

00:45:45.260 --> 00:45:46.900
in that direction is --
is sort of a testament

00:45:46.900 --> 00:45:50.000
to the way that it was structured.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:53.630
I think that's it.

00:45:53.630 --> 00:45:54.930
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:45:54.930 --> 00:45:57.370
Mr. Panjwani?

00:45:57.370 --> 00:45:58.670
&gt;&gt; Raza Panjawani: Thank you.

00:45:58.670 --> 00:46:01.770
We believe that a nexus
to copyright infringement

00:46:01.770 --> 00:46:05.970
within 1201 cures a number of
the issues that have manifested

00:46:05.970 --> 00:46:11.470
over the last 5 to 10 years,
such as the issues of access

00:46:11.470 --> 00:46:15.900
to consumer devices that have
software embedded within them

00:46:15.900 --> 00:46:20.040
and a variety of other competitive
issues that have been implicated.

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:23.180
But taking this back for a moment
to the discussion we've just had

00:46:23.180 --> 00:46:29.440
on the right of access and where
it exists in the copyright law,

00:46:29.440 --> 00:46:32.630
Section 1201 -- it sounds like
what we're hearing here is

00:46:32.630 --> 00:46:35.190
that Congress intended
to create an --

00:46:35.190 --> 00:46:38.240
a exclusive right of
access for authors.

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:41.570
And I don't think we should
be afraid of considering this

00:46:41.570 --> 00:46:46.600
in terms of, well, if we have a
nexus of infringement in 1201,

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:48.160
then what happens to
the right of access.

00:46:48.160 --> 00:46:51.020 position:56%
And I think that we should have a
debate on the right of access rather

00:46:51.020 --> 00:46:53.590
than on a prohibition
on circumvention.

00:46:53.590 --> 00:46:56.030 position:56%
If Congress wanted to create a right
of access, they could have put it

00:46:56.030 --> 00:46:59.610
in Section 106 with the rest of the
exclusive rights granted to authors

00:46:59.610 --> 00:47:02.050
of copyright-protected works.

00:47:02.050 --> 00:47:06.120
Now, again, looking at some of the
legislative history and the text

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:08.210
of the statute, there's
no discussion of, well,

00:47:08.210 --> 00:47:09.510
we wanted to create
this right of access,

00:47:09.510 --> 00:47:12.890 position:56%
it's we want to create incentives to
enter digital markets and we think

00:47:12.890 --> 00:47:15.250
that this is a necessary step

00:47:15.250 --> 00:47:19.450
to incentivize entry
into digital markets.

00:47:19.450 --> 00:47:25.030
And I don't think that,
you know, a explicit right

00:47:25.030 --> 00:47:27.550
of access was contemplated
at that point.

00:47:27.550 --> 00:47:29.550
In fact, the WIPO Treaty
says, you know,

00:47:29.550 --> 00:47:33.380
we want to have adequate
protections for technical measures

00:47:33.380 --> 00:47:37.070
that are employed by
authors in the protection

00:47:37.070 --> 00:47:40.680
of their rights granted
under, you know, this --

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:43.500 position:56%
this Treaty which we would then
read in the case of the U.S. Statute

00:47:43.500 --> 00:47:48.310 position:56%
under this Title, which is 106,
which is reproduction, distribution,

00:47:48.310 --> 00:47:51.460
public performance and so forth.

00:47:51.460 --> 00:47:54.060
In particular, I would say,
you know, the examples that --

00:47:54.060 --> 00:47:57.760
that Mr. Band and Mr. Adler
were just discussing, you know,

00:47:57.760 --> 00:47:59.750
I think you perhaps
underestimate the creativity

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:02.630
of plaintiff's counsel and their
ability to identify a violation

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:05.170
of 106 in any of these
given particular instances

00:48:05.170 --> 00:48:08.560
where you're afraid that
copyright infringement does not get

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:10.620
at the behavior.

00:48:10.620 --> 00:48:12.680
There may be an access to a copy.

00:48:12.680 --> 00:48:14.520
Well, where did the copy come from?

00:48:14.520 --> 00:48:17.830 position:56%
You know, is the copy lawfully
possessed at the time of the access,

00:48:17.830 --> 00:48:19.220
you know, in the case of a rental?

00:48:19.220 --> 00:48:20.520
Was it sold?

00:48:20.520 --> 00:48:21.820
Well, it was rented.

00:48:21.820 --> 00:48:23.120
After the rent -- rental expires,

00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:24.510
do you still lawfully
possess that copy?

00:48:24.510 --> 00:48:26.420
So I think there are a number
of ways of solving this issue

00:48:26.420 --> 00:48:30.060
that don't require such a broad
prohibition on circumvention

00:48:30.060 --> 00:48:34.340
that burdens all other
non-infringing uses.

00:48:34.340 --> 00:48:38.380
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Can you speak
to Mr. Adler's distinction

00:48:38.380 --> 00:48:42.540
between access control prohibition
of 1201(a) versus copy controls

00:48:42.540 --> 00:48:45.020
in 1201(b), the anti-trafficking
prohibitions?

00:48:45.020 --> 00:48:48.150
I mean, that seems
like, statutorily,

00:48:48.150 --> 00:48:51.280
they've made that difference and
we could rely on that as opposed

00:48:51.280 --> 00:48:53.540
to creativity of plaintiff's
counsel.

00:48:53.540 --> 00:48:55.710
&gt;&gt; Raza Panjawani:
It's been our position

00:48:55.710 --> 00:49:00.730 position:56%
that the anti-trafficking provisions
distinction between copy protection

00:49:00.730 --> 00:49:03.230
and access protection,
as far as implementation,

00:49:03.230 --> 00:49:06.390
are largely indistinguishable;
that a TPM used

00:49:06.390 --> 00:49:10.680
for access control is a TPM
used for copy control often.

00:49:10.680 --> 00:49:14.030
And we've approached that
in the exemption process

00:49:14.030 --> 00:49:17.550
as addressing them more
or less as the same.

00:49:17.550 --> 00:49:19.210
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Because
you're seeing the merged use

00:49:19.210 --> 00:49:22.450
of controls in the industry?

00:49:22.450 --> 00:49:23.750
&gt;&gt; Raza Panjawani: Right.

00:49:23.750 --> 00:49:25.670
In practice, while the
Statute recognizes them

00:49:25.670 --> 00:49:29.550 position:56%
as two separate types of control,
in practice, we see them implemented

00:49:29.550 --> 00:49:33.050
as more or less as the same.

00:49:33.050 --> 00:49:34.350
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:49:34.350 --> 00:49:35.650
Mr. Pierre-Louis?

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:36.950
&gt;&gt; Stan Pierre-Louis: I -- I just
wanted to add that in our industry,

00:49:36.950 --> 00:49:40.210
that's not the case because
you have console manufacturers

00:49:40.210 --> 00:49:42.460
and you have publishers
who produce discs.

00:49:42.460 --> 00:49:46.410
They have to interoperate, but they
do have separate types of access

00:49:46.410 --> 00:49:47.710
and copy controls within them.

00:49:47.710 --> 00:49:50.000
So in our industry,
we've seen the benefit

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:52.320
of having both of those available.

00:49:52.320 --> 00:49:55.530
It's -- it's important to
recognize that we're not trying

00:49:55.530 --> 00:49:59.120 position:56%
to identify infringers, we're trying
to identify and cultivate consumers,

00:49:59.120 --> 00:50:01.640
and so, all of these
things help us do that.

00:50:01.640 --> 00:50:05.370
And so, access to the work
becomes an important way

00:50:05.370 --> 00:50:08.000
of distinguishing the
different uses users want.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:10.770
Some want it on mobile, some want
it online, some want it on a disc

00:50:10.770 --> 00:50:12.740
in a counsel -- in a console.

00:50:12.740 --> 00:50:17.820 position:56%
And I think all of these rules allow
us to play within that framework

00:50:17.820 --> 00:50:20.070
and meet customers where they are.

00:50:20.070 --> 00:50:23.580
This is not academic for
us, this is business.

00:50:23.580 --> 00:50:27.420
And so, you know, making
a nexus to infringement

00:50:27.420 --> 00:50:32.370
in many ways harms the
consumers because, right now,

00:50:32.370 --> 00:50:34.920
and I think this is the -- the
correct interpretation of the law,

00:50:34.920 --> 00:50:37.380
possession of the work is -- is
not what's infringing, it's --

00:50:37.380 --> 00:50:39.580
it's the various uses some
may make, and now we're --

00:50:39.580 --> 00:50:42.010
we're trying to implicate
more on consumers there.

00:50:42.010 --> 00:50:46.450 position:56%
I think it's important to recognize
that that access control allows them

00:50:46.450 --> 00:50:50.780
to make uses and that's what
we're trying to cultivate.

00:50:50.780 --> 00:50:52.080
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:50:52.080 --> 00:50:53.930
Mr. Slover?

00:50:53.930 --> 00:50:55.230
&gt;&gt; George Slover: Yes.

00:50:55.230 --> 00:50:57.590
I wanted to go back to your
earlier question about ownership

00:50:57.590 --> 00:51:02.700
versus other models
of rental or so forth.

00:51:02.700 --> 00:51:06.410
I think ownership is
the core focus --

00:51:06.410 --> 00:51:11.950
the rights of a consumer who owns
a product, to be able to use it.

00:51:11.950 --> 00:51:18.510
And I think you should be careful,
you know, ownership can be written

00:51:18.510 --> 00:51:23.830
around by lawyers so that what the
consumer thinks is ownership really

00:51:23.830 --> 00:51:25.130
isn't ownership.

00:51:25.130 --> 00:51:27.730
So I think it needs to be broader

00:51:27.730 --> 00:51:30.260
than just a legal definition
of ownership.

00:51:30.260 --> 00:51:34.940
But it's the concept of the
consumer's rights and dominion

00:51:34.940 --> 00:51:40.080
over the product that they -- that
they've paid for, that they have.

00:51:40.080 --> 00:51:45.000
And -- and I think it -- a useful
starting point is to try to,

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:49.420
if possible, clear the
smoke around the --

00:51:49.420 --> 00:51:55.050
the technology and sort of
the complexities of software

00:51:55.050 --> 00:51:59.720
and everything, and try to think
of the -- I -- the -- when --

00:51:59.720 --> 00:52:03.160
when the DMCA was passed, there
was sort of a recognition,

00:52:03.160 --> 00:52:05.470
we need a new legal construct

00:52:05.470 --> 00:52:10.650
to bring the traditional copyright
protections into the digital age.

00:52:10.650 --> 00:52:15.920
Well, I think on the other side, we
need a recognition that the tried

00:52:15.920 --> 00:52:22.930
and true incidence of ownership
should still have value of and --

00:52:22.930 --> 00:52:25.910 position:56%
and presence in the digital economy.

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:32.220
So, for example, taking the
auto software situation,

00:52:32.220 --> 00:52:36.550
if it was something that a consumer
used to be able to do in his garage

00:52:36.550 --> 00:52:41.340
with a screwdriver, that
was not a copyright issue,

00:52:41.340 --> 00:52:46.640 position:56%
it was not an infringement issue, it
was not a -- an inappropriate use.

00:52:46.640 --> 00:52:54.230
If the same thing in the -- the
new world requires getting access

00:52:54.230 --> 00:52:57.890
to the software in order to
be able to make an adjustment,

00:52:57.890 --> 00:53:01.390
the fact that there's a
technological protection measure

00:53:01.390 --> 00:53:05.450
on top of it should not change the
ultimate calculus and objective.

00:53:05.450 --> 00:53:09.030
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: So the Copyright
Office is separately undergoing a

00:53:09.030 --> 00:53:12.960
study on software in -- in
embedded devices, and I'm wondering

00:53:12.960 --> 00:53:15.470
if what you're saying -- or if
there could be some consensus

00:53:15.470 --> 00:53:19.060
around treating software in these
embedded devices differently

00:53:19.060 --> 00:53:23.130
than TPMs protecting expressive
works, if that might be another way

00:53:23.130 --> 00:53:26.850
to slice it, rather than
a nexus to infringement?

00:53:26.850 --> 00:53:29.780
&gt;&gt; George Slover: Well, I'm not a
copyright lawyer and our experience

00:53:29.780 --> 00:53:31.250
at Consumers Union -- our --

00:53:31.250 --> 00:53:33.220
our point of entry into all

00:53:33.220 --> 00:53:37.290
of this was really the
mobile phone unlocking effort

00:53:37.290 --> 00:53:40.390
that we helped lead.

00:53:40.390 --> 00:53:44.460
So I can't speak too
definitively to the broader issue.

00:53:44.460 --> 00:53:49.690
I do see sort of a -- a big
picture conceptual distinction

00:53:49.690 --> 00:53:57.840
between the core creative works
and access to books and movies

00:53:57.840 --> 00:54:01.210
and songs, on the one hand,

00:54:01.210 --> 00:54:06.850
and products that you now can't
use unless you have software that's

00:54:06.850 --> 00:54:08.370
functioning inside them.

00:54:08.370 --> 00:54:13.180
So what's brought us in, the --
thee concern that we saw was that,

00:54:13.180 --> 00:54:18.820
you know, Internet software-enabled
devices, both in the Internet

00:54:18.820 --> 00:54:23.180
of Things and then the things that
just sort of operate internally.

00:54:23.180 --> 00:54:27.440
But I wouldn't want to
put my finger on the scale

00:54:27.440 --> 00:54:30.180
of some of these other issues.

00:54:30.180 --> 00:54:31.480
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:54:31.480 --> 00:54:32.780
Mr. Adler?

00:54:32.780 --> 00:54:34.080
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: Yeah.

00:54:34.080 --> 00:54:35.380
I just wanted to make two points.

00:54:35.380 --> 00:54:38.320
One is, if I understood
Mr. Panjwani correctly,

00:54:38.320 --> 00:54:42.230 position:56%
he suggested that an alternative
approach by Congress would have been

00:54:42.230 --> 00:54:45.790
to include access within
the exclusive rights enjoyed

00:54:45.790 --> 00:54:48.430
by a copyright owner under 106.

00:54:48.430 --> 00:54:50.100
And I would only have
to assume that --

00:54:50.100 --> 00:54:52.850
that the constituency
that he represents and --

00:54:52.850 --> 00:54:56.010
and that, for example, Jonathan
represents in their criticism

00:54:56.010 --> 00:55:00.150
of 1201, would oppose
vigorously such a notion,

00:55:00.150 --> 00:55:02.810
because that would
lend the idea that --

00:55:02.810 --> 00:55:07.250
that access itself had the
attributes of a property right,

00:55:07.250 --> 00:55:11.630
which is what exclusive rights
under 106 really are about,

00:55:11.630 --> 00:55:17.150 position:56%
rather than this being a question of
whether or not somebody who is going

00:55:17.150 --> 00:55:22.710
to use their works in a marketplace
manner, making them available

00:55:22.710 --> 00:55:26.670
to people but expecting to be
able to assert certain terms

00:55:26.670 --> 00:55:30.310
for condition of availability
and use would be able to control

00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:34.710
that in the first instance by
controlling access to the work.

00:55:34.710 --> 00:55:37.190
And then, the second point I
was going to make is is that,

00:55:37.190 --> 00:55:39.110
just to be clear, I -- I --

00:55:39.110 --> 00:55:45.040
I was kind of concerned about
seeing the emphasis in the notice

00:55:45.040 --> 00:55:51.100
on talking about 1201 outside
of core copyright concerns.

00:55:51.100 --> 00:55:54.550
I'm not sure I have any real
grasp of what that phrase,

00:55:54.550 --> 00:55:57.980
core copyright concerns,
actually entails,

00:55:57.980 --> 00:56:02.370 position:56%
but it would be a tremendous mistake
to equate that with the notion

00:56:02.370 --> 00:56:06.440
of a nexus to infringement,
because obviously,

00:56:06.440 --> 00:56:10.610
copyright concerns drive far
more than simply the notion

00:56:10.610 --> 00:56:14.680
of whether one of these specific
exclusive rights is violated.

00:56:14.680 --> 00:56:18.550 position:56%
We've talked, you know, always talk
about the incentives to create works

00:56:18.550 --> 00:56:22.190
of original expression in the
first place, which is driven

00:56:22.190 --> 00:56:25.100
to a large part by the
private incentives involved

00:56:25.100 --> 00:56:27.490
with the benefits of copyright.

00:56:27.490 --> 00:56:30.980
And I think the discussion
we had a little bit earlier

00:56:30.980 --> 00:56:35.800
about access relating itself
to the value of using a work

00:56:35.800 --> 00:56:38.060
without infringing it or without

00:56:38.060 --> 00:56:41.500 position:56%
in any way implicating the exclusive
rights of the rights holder,

00:56:41.500 --> 00:56:46.330
that is a core copyright
concern, and we shouldn't treat

00:56:46.330 --> 00:56:49.490
that notion very narrowly
so that we only think

00:56:49.490 --> 00:56:51.920
that core copyright concerns arise

00:56:51.920 --> 00:56:54.780
when we're discussing
about infringement.

00:56:54.780 --> 00:56:56.510
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: And I
think that goes really

00:56:56.510 --> 00:56:59.990
to the point Mr. Slover was
